1. Project Background & Study Objectives¶

This research is to further learn the customer data, study the pattern of the customers' churn rate, apply machine learning methods to train the prediction model, test the model and conduct sales simulation by apply the chosen model.
There are four datasets in total for this study. All the dataset are a real dataset from a Telecommunication company. For the study purposes, all the sensitive information has been removed or replaced from the dataset.

The goal and objectives of this study are to answer the following questions:

1) How to define the Churn Rate;¶
2) What are the factors relavant to Churn Rate;¶
3) How to define the time window when customer churn happening;¶
4) How to define the benefits¶
5) What's the effects of the training models;¶
6) Simulation of Sales and find out ways to reduce customer churn rate.¶

2. Methodologies¶

The methods and key steps of this study will include:¶

1) Data Feature Engineering¶
2) Exploratory Analysis on the Dataset¶
3) Application of Derivative Indicators¶
4) Cluster Analysis using Kmeans and Birch¶
5) Generating Rules Set using Decision Tree¶
6) Obtaining Churn Scores by Neural Networks¶
7) Application of Trained Models for Sales Simulation¶

# Generate bar chart by group 
def M_GphDes(x, y, type = '', printdata = True): 

    if type == '%':
        tmpdf = pd.crosstab(index = y, columns = x, normalize = "columns")
    else:
        tmpdf = pd.crosstab(index = y, columns = x)
    
    if printdata:
        print(tmpdf.T)

    colorstep0 = 1/len(tmpdf.index)
    for i in range(len(tmpdf.index)):
        if i == 0:
            colorstep = colorstep0 / 2 # Avoid all blank bar
            sns.barplot(data = tmpdf.loc[[tmpdf.index[i]]], 
                        color = str(colorstep), label = tmpdf.index[i])
            base = tmpdf.loc[tmpdf.index[i]]
        else:
            sns.barplot(data = tmpdf.loc[[tmpdf.index[i]]],
                        color = str(colorstep), bottom = base, label = tmpdf.index[i])
            base = base + tmpdf.loc[tmpdf.index[i]]
        colorstep = colorstep + colorstep0 
    plt.xticks(rotation = 'vertical') #  Applied matplotlib.text 
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

# Search extreme values and produce simple report
# scanmethod: the definition of extreme values- 5 standard deviation +/ 5 standard errors
# return: dataframe with all variables query results. 
def M_ScanVar(dfname, scanmethod = '5sd'):

    dfres = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['Mean', 'SD', 'Min', 'Max', 'Min Extreme', 'Max Extreme'])
    for colname in dfname.columns:
        try:
            if scanmethod == '5sd':
                std = dfname[colname].std()
                mean = dfname[colname].mean()
                dfres.loc[colname] = [std, mean, 
                    dfname[colname].min(), dfname[colname].max(),
                    pd.Series(dfname[colname] < mean - 5 * std).sum(),
                    pd.Series(dfname[colname] > mean + 5 * std).sum()
                    ]
        except: # non-numeric variable, return errors
            print(colname + '  Unable to Analyze')
    return dfres

def M_VarBin(dfname, collist = [], binmethod = 'cut', 
             binnum = 10, keepvar = True, iscat = True, todumm = False):
    
    dfnew = copy.copy(dfname)
    
    if len(collist) == 0:
        collist = dfnew.columns
        
    catlabel = None
    if not iscat: # Varible become numeric instead of categorical after the change 
            catlabel = range(binnum)
            
    for var in collist:
        if binmethod == 'cut':
            dfnew[var + '_bin'] = pd.cut(dfnew[var], bins = binnum,
                                    labels = catlabel, duplicates = 'drop')
            if todumm:
                dfnew = M_dumm(dfnew, [var + '_bin']) # Change to Dummy Variable Group 
            elif not iscat: # Fix a bug in pandas
                dfnew[var + '_bin'] = dfnew[var + '_bin'].astype('int')
        elif binmethod == 'qcut':
            dfnew[var + '_qbin'] = pd.qcut(dfnew[var], q = binnum, 
                                    labels = catlabel, duplicates = 'drop')
            if todumm:
                dfnew = M_dumm(dfnew, [var + '_qbin'])
            elif not iscat:
                dfnew[var + '_qbin'] = dfnew[var + '_qbin'].astype('int')

    if not keepvar: # Delete Original Variables 
        dfnew.drop(columns = collist, inplace = True)

    return dfnew

def M_dumm(dfname, collist = [], namesuffix = '', drop = True):

    dfnew = copy.copy(dfname)
    if len(collist) == 0: # Prepare Variables Name List
        collist = dfname.columns
        
    binlist = []
    for colname in collist: # Filter Bivariate 
        if len(set(dfname[colname])) == 2: 
            binlist.append(colname)
            collist.remove(colname)

    prefixlist = []
    for colname in collist: # Prepare Prefix of Dummy Variables 
        prefixlist.append(colname + namesuffix)

    binprefixlist = []
    for colname in binlist: # Prepare Prefix of Dummy Bivariate 
        binprefixlist.append(colname + namesuffix)

    if len(collist) > 0:
        dfdumm = pd.get_dummies(dfname[collist].astype('str'), prefix = prefixlist)
        dfnew = pd.merge(dfnew, dfdumm, left_index = True, right_index = True)

    if len(binlist) > 0:
        dfdumm = pd.get_dummies(dfname[binlist].astype('str'), 
                                drop_first = True, prefix = binprefixlist)
        dfnew = pd.merge(dfnew, dfdumm, left_index = True, right_index = True)

    if drop:
        dfnew.drop(columns = collist, inplace = True)
        dfnew.drop(columns = binlist, inplace = True)

    return dfnew

def M_CheckMissing(dfname):

    cnt = 0
    for col in dfname.columns:
        # MisCount = len(dfname[col]) - len(dfname.loc[dfname[col] == dfname[col]])
        MisCount = dfname[col].isna().sum()
        if MisCount > 0:
            print(col, MisCount)
            cnt += 1
    if cnt == 0:
        print('No missing values in all variables.')
    else:
        print(cnt, 'variables contain missing values.')

def M_FillNa(colname, repval = 'mean', naval = []): 

    TmpLst = copy.copy(colname) # Protect original data 

    if len(naval) > 0: # Replace defined missing values
        TmpLst = TmpLst.replace(naval, np.nan) 
    
    if repval == 'random':
        for i in range(TmpLst.shape[0]): # Go through all values 
            if TmpLst.iloc[i] != TmpLst.iloc[i]: # If yes, process missing values
                while True: # Use numeric values to replace 
                    rndrepval = TmpLst.iloc[random.randint(0, TmpLst.shape[0] - 1)]
                    if rndrepval == rndrepval: # Make sure extract effective values. 
                        break
                TmpLst.iloc[i] = rndrepval
    elif repval == 'mean':
        TmpLst = TmpLst.fillna(TmpLst.mean())
    else:
        TmpLst = TmpLst.fillna(repval)

    return TmpLst

In [44]:
# Generate intermediate variable for trend and fluctuation analysis 
dfcustcall['Peak_mins_month'] = dfcustcall.Peak_mins * dfcustcall.month
dfcustcall['OffPeak_mins_month'] = dfcustcall.OffPeak_mins * dfcustcall.month
dfcustcall['Weekend_mins_month'] = dfcustcall.Weekend_mins * dfcustcall.month
dfcustcall['month_month'] = dfcustcall.month * dfcustcall.month

# Generate all sum-up values grouping by Customer_ID
dfsum = dfcustcall.groupby('Customer_ID').agg('sum')
dfmean = dfcustcall.groupby('Customer_ID').agg('mean')
dfmin = dfcustcall.groupby('Customer_ID').agg('min')
dfmax = dfcustcall.groupby('Customer_ID').agg('max')
dfn = dfcustcall.groupby('Customer_ID').agg('size') # Here, shouldn't use count()

# Calculate the Trend and Fluctuation of Related Variables 
dfsum['Peak_mins_Trend'] =  (dfn * dfsum.Peak_mins_month - dfsum.Peak_mins * dfsum.month) / (dfn * dfsum.month_month - dfsum.month * dfsum.month)
dfsum['OffPeak_mins_Trend'] = (dfn * dfsum.OffPeak_mins_month - dfsum.OffPeak_mins * dfsum.month) / (dfn*dfsum.month_month - dfsum.month * dfsum.month)
dfsum['Weekend_mins_Trend'] =  (dfn * dfsum.Weekend_mins_month - dfsum.Weekend_mins * dfsum.month) / (dfn*dfsum.month_month - dfsum.month * dfsum.month)

dfsum['Peak_mins_Fluctuation'] =  (dfmax.Peak_mins - dfmin.Peak_mins) / dfmean.Peak_mins
dfsum['OffPeak_mins_Fluctuation'] =  (dfmax.OffPeak_mins - dfmin.OffPeak_mins) / dfmean.OffPeak_mins
dfsum['Weekend_mins_Fluctuation'] =  (dfmax.Weekend_mins - dfmin.Weekend_mins) / dfmean.Weekend_mins

# Fill in the missing values with random values 
dfsum['Peak_mins_Fluctuation'] = M_FillNa(dfsum.Peak_mins_Fluctuation, repval = 'random')
dfsum['OffPeak_mins_Fluctuation'] = M_FillNa(dfsum.OffPeak_mins_Fluctuation, repval = 'random')
dfsum['Weekend_mins_Fluctuation'] = M_FillNa(dfsum.Weekend_mins_Fluctuation, repval = 'random')

3.1.7 Calculate Aggregate Indicators¶

Aggregate the following indicators for 6 months:¶

1) Number of Phone Calls during Peak Time, Non-Peak Time, Weekend¶
2) Duration of Phone Calls during Peak Time, Non-Peak Time, Weekend¶
3) Duration of Interntional Phone Calls¶
4) Cost for Domestic Phone Calls¶
In [45]:
# Aggregate by grouping Customer_ID
# Frequencies and Duration of Domestic Phone Calls  
dfsum['National_calls'] = dfsum.Peak_calls + dfsum.OffPeak_calls + dfsum.Weekend_calls
dfsum['National_mins'] = dfsum.Peak_mins + dfsum.OffPeak_mins + dfsum.Weekend_mins

# Ratio during Peak Time, Non-Peak Time, and Weekend
dfsum['Peak_mins_Ratio'] = dfsum.Peak_mins / dfsum.National_mins
dfsum['OffPeak_mins_Ratio'] = dfsum.OffPeak_mins / dfsum.National_mins
dfsum['Weekend_mins_Ratio'] = dfsum.Weekend_mins / dfsum.National_mins

# Total Call Duraiton Ratio
dfsum['All_calls_mins'] = dfsum.National_mins + dfsum.International_mins
# International Call Duration Ratio
dfsum['International_mins_Ratio'] = dfsum.International_mins / dfsum.All_calls_mins

# Average Call Duration during Peak Time, Non-Peak Time, and Weekend
dfsum['AvePeak'] = dfsum.Peak_mins / dfsum.Peak_calls
dfsum['AveOffPeak'] = dfsum.OffPeak_mins / dfsum.OffPeak_calls
dfsum['AveWeekend'] = dfsum.Weekend_mins / dfsum.Weekend_calls
dfsum['AveNational'] = dfsum.National_mins / dfsum.National_calls

# Replace the missing value with zero. 
dfsum.fillna({'AvePeak' : 0, 'AveOffPeak' : 0, 
              'AveWeekend' : 0, 'AveNational': 0}, 
             inplace = True)

Customer Segmentation by Phone Bill Usage¶

The customers are segmented into the following groups by domestic phone call duration:¶
1) Low Usage Users: the phone call duration is below the average duration - 1 standard deviation¶
2) Medium Usage Users: the phone call duration is within the average duration +/- 1 standard deviation¶
3) High Usage Users: the phone call duration is within the average duration between +/- 1 standard deviation and +/- 2 standard deviation¶
4) Super Usage Users: the phone call duration is more than the average duration + 2 standard deviation¶
In [48]:
std = dfsum.National_mins.std()
mean = dfsum.National_mins.mean()
dfsum['National_mins_cls'] = pd.cut(dfsum.National_mins, 
                bins = [-np.Inf, mean - std, mean + std, mean + 2 * std, np.Inf], 
                labels = ['Low Usage', 'Medium Usage', 'High Usage', 'Super Usage'])

dfsum['Mins_charge'] = dfsum.National_mins - dfsum.Free_mins * 6
dfsum['call_cost_per_min'] = (dfsum.Peak_rate * dfsum.Peak_mins_sum + 
            dfsum.OffPeak_rate * dfsum.OffPeak_mins_sum + 
            dfsum.Weekend_rate * dfsum.Weekend_mins_sum) / dfsum.National_mins

dfsum['Total_call_cost'] = dfsum.actual_call_cost + \
            dfsum.International_mins_sum * dfsum.International_rate / 100

The telecommunication company plans to set a high discount rate at 30%, considering that the response rate has been around 50% with high discount incentives in the past years, the purpose of the sales simulation is to find how many target customers and who should be included into the retaining plan so as to minimize the possible loss (if any) after the planned radical sales retaining plan. From this study, we can learn that, when the sales plan covers 12.93% of the churn customers, the net profit will reach the maximum 136.6 RMB, which is positive. Therefore, it is suggested for the sales department to promote the sales plan to 13% of lost customers which are 2411 customers to retain them stay in the telecommunication company, so that the company not only can break even for the high discount retaining incentive promotion but also can increase the revenue by cross selling and up selling their other new products and services to the retained customers.
